      "question": "Do dark-colored roof shingles make my house hotter in South Florida?",
      "answer": "No, modern dark-colored shingles with cool roof technology do NOT significantly increase cooling costs in South Florida. This is an outdated myth based on old shingle technology from 20+ years ago. Today''s ENERGY STAR rated dark shingles use specially engineered reflective granules that reflect up to 60-75% of infrared radiation (heat) while maintaining rich dark colors. The Solar Reflectance Index (SRI) difference between modern cool roof dark shingles (SRI 25-40) and light shingles (SRI 40-55) translates to only 10-15°F surface temperature difference and less than 2°F impact on living space temperature with proper insulation. Florida Solar Energy Center testing showed only 3% cooling cost difference ($47 annually) between white and dark gray ENERGY STAR shingles when homes had proper R-38 insulation and ventilation. The reality is that attic ventilation and insulation have 5-6 times more impact on energy efficiency than shingle color. A properly ventilated attic with R-38 insulation performs excellently with dark shingles, while poor ventilation creates problems even with white shingles. Modern technology has eliminated the energy penalty of dark colors while preserving their aesthetic advantages."
